  "text": "One common difficulty in quantifying mortality is incorporating spatial processes. For motile organisms, such as bear and elk, spatial variation in food availability or predator populations can have important effects on survivorship (e.g., [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , and in general, population viability is often strongly influenced by spatial relationships [CITATION_3] . With sessile organisms such as plants, spatial effects can be even more direct, since such organisms can only ''move'' via births and deaths (e.g., Deutschman 1995, Bolker et al. 2003) . In this paper, we examine spatial elements of mortality risk by specifically addressing their role in the mortality of forest trees.",
